Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 11 numeric variables that describe different characteristics of the 1599 red wines in the data set. quality is a categorical variable that represents the score of a given red wine according to an expert.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Quality scores have very little variance; most wines in the dataset have a score of 5 or 6 (1319 out of 1599 - 82.5%). This is the only qualitative variable.

Most variables have a somewhat normal distribution, usually with longer right tails, with the exception of ctric acid which has a large count for value 0, and a volatile distribution. It is also worth noting the well behaved distributions for both density and ph.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The idea is to explore how the 11 quantitative variables relate to quality. Also it will be interesting to see how these variables interact with each other, especially the group of fixed acidity, volatile acidity and citric acid (ph also may be related to this group). And the group of free sulfur oxide, total sulfur oxide, and maybe sulphates.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The first long right tail was for residual sugar. The difference between the log transform and a histogram that omits the top 4% of the values, aside from the various gaps in the log transform, does not give additional insights.

The histogram for alcohol also was log transformed, but again, aside shortening the tail in a similar way than omitting the top 4%, it does not give any further insights.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

Alcohol has a strong correlation with density; however, alcohol is the variable with the highest correlation to quality, while density has a negligible correlation with quality. The group fixed acidity, citric acid and ph are highly correlated between them. Volatile acidity has strong correlation with only citric acid from this group; interestingly it is also the acidic variable with the strongest correlation to quality. Sulphates has a strong correlation to chlorides, but sulphates doubles its correlation to quality compared to chlorides. Free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide also have strong correlation. Both have low correlation with quality, but total sulfur dioxide had a stronger correlation; however, looking at the conditional means plot there is no clear relationship with quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Residual sugar has low correlation with all the other variables, including quality.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Fixed acidity and ph.

Multivariate Plots Section

I will start exploring the relationship between volatile acidity, citric acid, and quality. On the x axis there seems to be larger dots (higher score quality) to the left; whereas on the y axis it seems that there are dots of all sizes throughout. The relationship between volatile acidity and citric acid is shown in the plot by the smooth line.

I will facet this plot. The relationship between volatile acidity and citric acid is consistent for all the quality scores. Since I am trying to build a model to predict quality, I confirm my idea of using only volatile acidity in my model.

Now, volatile acidity, alcohol, and quality. Alcohol and volatile acidity are the two variables with higher correlation to quality.

I will try a faceted plot The relationship between alcohol and volatile acidity, for different qualities is not consistent. Therefore I confirm the use of these two variables in my model, for I will consider them as independent.

Now I will build the model: m1 is simply quality as a function of alcohol, m2 adds volatile acidity as an explanatory variable to m1, and m3 adds sulphates as an explanatory variable to m2.

##     data = red_wines)

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Interactions confirmed the features described in previous sections.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the strengths and limitations of your model.

Given the conditional median plots from the Bivariate Analysis section, a linear model was chosen to predict quality scores. There were initially five varibles of interest for this plot: alcohol, volatile acidity, sulphates, citric acid, and total sulfur dioxide. Total sulfur dioxide was discarded with its conditional median plot. Also volatile acidity and citric acid were found to have a strong relationship, given the plots for these variables and their relationship with quality, only volatile acidity was left in the model. This considerations gave rise to the m3 model with only three explanatory variables, alcohol, volatile acidity, and sulphates. The dataset can be thought as relatively small, so in order to avoid overfitting to this dataset, the relatively low R^2 value can be thought as sufficient. Also, bear in mind that even though given by experts, quality scores are subjective values; and most scores are either 5 or 6. Possibly, a better model could be built with a larger ddataset, and a quality score variable with larger variance.

Reflection

This dataset contains several chemical characteristics of red wines, and a quality varible that contains quality scores for each of the 1599 observations. Initially, keeping in mind that the final goal was to build a model that explained quality as a function of the chemical characteristics of red wines, a univariate exploration and analysis was conducted. The first important finding was that quality did not had too much variance; most of the scores were either 5 or 6. The fact that citric acid didnt had a normal distribution aslo was important for its exclusion of the model at the end.

In the bivariate exploration and analysis, five potential variables were recognized as variables of interest for their correlation to quality. It was also found a strong correlation between two of the variables of interest, namely volatile acidity and citric acid. Finally, conditional median plots gave insight in the linear relationship of quality and that variables of interest, except for total sulfur dioxide.

In the last section of Multivariate exploration and analysis, the previous findings were confirmed and the model was built.
